  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN213">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>maṇṭama raṭṭa mataṉuṭai nōṉṟāḷ</l>
<l>veṇkuṭai viḷakkum viṟaṟkeḻu vēntē</l>
<l>poṅkunī ruṭuttavim malartalai yulakattu</l>
<l>niṉṟalai vanta viruvarai niṉaippiṟ</l>
<l>ṟoṉṟuṟai tuppiṉiṉ pakaiñaru malla</l>
<l>ramarveṅ kāṭciyoṭu māṟetir peḻuntavar</l>
<l>niṉaiyuṅ kālai nīyu maṟṟavark</l>
<l>kaṉaiyai yallai yaṭumāṉ ṟōṉṟal</l>
<l>parantupaṭu nallicai yeyti maṟṟunī</l>
<l>yuyarntō rulaka meytip piṉṉu</l>
<l>moḻitta tāya mavarkkurit taṉṟē</l>
<l>yataṉāl, aṉṉa tātalu maṟivōy naṉṟu</l>
<l>miṉṉuṅ kēṇmati yicaivey yōyē</l>
<l>niṉṟa tuppoṭu niṉkuṟit teḻunta</l>
<l>veṇṇil kāṭci yiḷaiyōr tōṟpi</l>
<l>ṉiṉperuñ celvam yārkkeñ cuvaiyē</l>
<l>yamarveñ celva nīyavark kulaiyi</l>
<l>ṉikaḻuna ruvappap paḻiyeñ cuvaiyē</l>
<l>yataṉā, loḻikati lattainiṉ maṟaṉē valvirain</l>
<l>teḻumati vāḻkaniṉ ṉuḷḷa maḻintōrk</l>
<l>kēma mākuniṉ ṟāṇiḻaṉ mayaṅkātu</l>
<l>ceytal vēṇṭumā ṉaṉṟē vāṉō</l>
<l>rarumpeṟa lulakat tāṉṟavar</l>
<l>vitumpuṟu viruppoṭu viruntetir koḷaṟkē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O victorious king whose while parasol shines brightly, (2)</l>
<l>with a powerful sturdy foot, who killed in rushing fight, (1)</l>
<l>if you think of the two [men] who have come to your place (4)</l>
<l>in this world of blooming are yoked with foaming water, (3)</l>
<l>they are not enemies of you with a vigour than stays of old, (5)</l>
<l>those who have risen in opposition with a view keen on a fight, (6)</l>
<l>and you, at the time you think about [it], are not</l>
<l>like those others, o appearance on a murderous animal. (7f.)</l>
<l>You, having attained widespread fame, (9)</l>
<l>after you have attained the world of the upper one, moreover (10)</l>
<l>the heritage you have finished with will be rightfully their’s. (11)</l>
<l>Therefore, you who know well that it will be thus, (12)</l>
<l>from now on listen, you keen on fame: (13)</l>
<l>If the young men [whose army is a] countless sight are defeated (15)</l>
<l>who have risen aiming at you with [still] lasting vigour, (14)</l>
<l>to whom will you leave your great wealth? (16)</l>
<l>O lord keen on a fight, if you are ruined by them, (17)</l>
<l>you will leave behind blame while those who despise you rejoice. (18)</l>
<l>Therefore, let your bravery by curbed. In great hast (19)</l>
<l>rise – let your heart live [long]. (20a-c)</l>
<l>Without that the shade of your foot would be obscured that is protection to those in ruin, (20d-21)</l>
<l>you must act well (22a-c)</l>
<l>in order to be received as a guest with tremorous/eager longing (24)</l>
<l>by those who ended up in the world difficult to obtain, (23)</l>
<l>	by the celestials. (22d)</l>
</lg>
